"{\"uid\": \"etonline.com-olympic-gymnast-aly-raisman-says-she-was-hospitalized-twice-after-complete-body-paralysis-229376\", \"text\": \"Aly Raismanis opening up about her health struggles. On the latest episode of theCall Her Daddypodcast, the 30-year-old Olympic gymnast detailed the two times she was hospitalized after having stroke-like symptoms.  \\\"I can not remember my name. I am slurring my words. I can barely speak,\\\" she said. \\\"Both times I was tested for a stroke because I literally could not move my body. It was so scary.\\\"  Raisman first experienced the scary medical issue amid the COVID-19 pandemic, which meant that she had to ride in the ambulance to the hospital alone.  \\\"They are asking me what my name is, but I can not remember my name or say what my name is,\\\" she recalled. \\\"I was aware enough to know like, 'Oh my God, I have two men [here and] I can not move my arms and my legs. I can not move my body. I can not speak. Like, what if they take advantage of me?'\\\"  The experience was triggering for Raisman as she's one of the athletes who suffered sexual abuse at the hand of former USA Gymnastics doctor Larry Nassar.\\u00a0Nassarpleaded guiltyto several charges in 2017 andwas sentencedto\\u00a040 to 175 years in prison the following year.  \\\"I was like really still struggling a lot with PTSD,\\\" Raisman said while recalling her ambulance ride. \\\"People do not realize how much it still lives with you when you have been through something traumatic.\\\"  Raisman experienced similar symptoms last year.  \\\"They would not release me because I could not sit up on my own. I needed help walking, going to the bathroom. It took me so long,\\\" she said. \\\"It was just the most [challenging] to be able to go from being like an athlete and being able to push myself so much to being able to literally not even be able to move my fingers, move my legs. I had complete body paralysis.\\\"  Raisman said that stress exacerbates her symptoms, so she has \\\"to be very on top\\\" of therapy and trusts her therapist to work with her if she's \\\"starting to feel off.\\\"  Now, Raisman is gearing up to head to Paris for the 2024 Olympic Games. While Raismanhas retired from gymnastics, she's set to be involved in this year's Games by serving as\\u00a0an official hospitality ambassador.  \\\"I am gonna be so busy,\\\" she said. \\\"There is gonna be a lot of triggers. I might see someone that maybe did not protect me in the past. So, it's working on that. It's very complicated.\\\"  RELATED CONTENT:  Video  News  Streaming  Olympics  \"}"